{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489879"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:20:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:20:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"769"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/769"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.08,0.51,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"769"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55321"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/769"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"769"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40849"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5486"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55321"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman is admitted from the Emergency Department with a two-day history of persistent right upper quadrant pain, associated with nausea and vomiting. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she is dehydrated and abdominal examination shows localised tenderness of the right upper quadrant. An ultrasound examination is arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings would be most in keeping with a diagnosis of acute cholecystitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A bile duct diameter of 18 mm","An echo-free mass in Hartmann\u0027s pouch","A stone in Hartmann\u0027s pouch","Pericholecystic fluid","Gallbladder wall thickness of 2 mm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture of an acutely unwell patient, with nausea, abdominal pain and tenderness in the right upper quadrant fits with a diagnosis of acute cholecystitis. Once the patient\u0027s pain and dehydration has been addressed, the next part of the process will be to look for the underlying cause of the problem - ie gallstones. The most expedient and appropriate investigation will be an upper abdominal ultrasound. The ultrasound will be used to define the structures in the right upper quadrant - the gallbladder, biliary tree and liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe common bile duct diameter is usually in the region of 4 mm, but a diameter of 7 mm is still in the normal range. A finding of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebile duct diameter of 18 mm \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be in keeping with biliary obstruction. Whilst a stone in the common bile duct might produce that degree of obstruction, it does not equate with acute cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStones will produce an echo and an \u003Cstrong\u003Eecho-free mass\u003C/strong\u003E within the gallbladder would suggest a polyp. Whilst the finding of a \u003Cstrong\u003Estone in Hartmann\u0027s pouch\u003C/strong\u003E might suggest some ongoing biliary problem, that problem may not be an inflammatory one. A \u003Cstrong\u003Egallbladder wall thickness of \u0026lt;3 mm\u003C/strong\u003E is within normal limits and could not be considered part of an inflammatory process. However, the presence of fluid around the gallbladder (\u003Cstrong\u003Epericholecystic fluid\u003C/strong\u003E) would add support to the clinical picture that there is an inflammatory process involving the gallbladder.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gallstones alone do not equal acute cholecystitis."],"references":["Gurusamy KS, Davidson BR. Gallstones. BMJ 2014;348:g2669. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24755732/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40849"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"769"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40849"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T17:08:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T17:09:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"769"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55321"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships